column1: Will anyone other than Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi be proclaimed caliph before 1 October 2017?
column5: ['Yes, while Baghdadi is alive', "Yes, after Baghdadi's death", 'No']
column6: ['Leader Entry/Exit', 'Security and Conflict']
column11: A global coalition of forces continues to hammer at the Islamic State and its leader Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi (Economist, Reuters). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: Abu Bakr al Baghdadi Counterterrorism experts on alert after audio urges militants to fight to the death

Because IS would not admit to his death even if it occurs.

The month September is almost over and we are nearing the first of October. Baghdadi has neither been killed nor is there any sign of him wanting to give up his post as Caliph.

Don't really have a process on this one, I'm just putting the odds on him being killed AND a new Caliph being announced in the next two weeks as extremely low probability. I don't see any reason why he would step down in this timeframe as well.
Updating to reflect upcoming close date (Oct. 1). "No" is now more likely.
Even if he is dead, IS will have no incentive to declare him dead.

Isis is wounded and on the hop so unlikely to be proclaiming anything! Latest reports say Baghdadi is still alive, so he would remain caliph.
As nice as it would be, I don't think this is happening in the next two weeks.

“A U.S. special operations task force tracked and killed three leaders, who allegedly oversaw weapons research and drone operations, in the valley this week, officials said.” (http://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-isis-intel-20170908-story.html) This is the area that Baghdadi is presumed to be located - even if he’s a target within the next two weeks, the group may not be sufficiently organised as to elect a new caliph in the remaining time frame.

Baghdadi is more than just a spiritual leader for ISIS. He is the Caliph, the "rightful heir" to a line of Caliphs decended from the hand picked successors to Muhammed himself. His death will be disputed for years just as Bin Laden's was, and it is likely that thousands of hours of pre recorded sermons and speeches of his remain somewhere encrypted, hiding on the web.

The jihadist group, which has used prophecies of an imminent apocalypse to marshal militants from around the world, is about to face its own End of Days on the battlefields of Syria and Iraq. Syrian government forces, backed by Iranian militias and spurred on by Russian air strikes, broke through IS’s defences around the eastern city of Deir ez-Zor on September 5th. Bashar al-Assad’s regime is preparing an assault to retake the entire city, ending the jihadists’ control over their last urban stronghold. Territorially, the militants are on the verge of defeat. They have lost about 90% of their “caliphate” in Iraq and 85% of their territory in Syria. American and Russian air strikes are picking off the group’s leaders as they hide in towns and villages south of Deir ez-Zor. The prophesied destruction of the crusader armies will have to wait

"Daesh leader Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi is dead, Syrian war monitor says" "Baghdadi’s apparent death or capture has been asserted several times over the past decade as his breakaway Al Qaeda faction gradually formed into Daesh. But the various reports later proved false or could not be substantiated." https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2017/07/11/daesh-leader-abu-bakr-al-baghdadi-is-dead-syrian-war-monitor-says.html

Based on consensus. Even if his death is confirmed in the next few weeks, chances of an official proclamation of a new leader seems highly unlikely. With their PR taking a hit with dwindling strongholds, they probably won't want to look even more disorganized.
(This forecast is the product of perverse incentives.)
Because I think he is still alive . Or, if he isn't, admitting his death would make ISIS look weak, which would be detrimental to their collective ego, especially at their current 'low point'.

Even he's dead, we assume he's alive until proven. Who can contest Baghdadi when he's alive? The biggest competitor is AQ, but Zawahiri already denounced him and the org is unlikely to contest sth they don't recognize. The claim can still come from a smaller group to benefit from the uncertainty around whether Baghdadi is dead or alive. Who can be the successor if he's dead? ISIS will need a leader and a new caliph would likely follow, but not sure who he will that be. We cannot rule out yet that he's not going to be declared dead before 1 October and a new caliphate will not be announced.

I have no idea if this man is dead or alive, but time is running out. If he's dead, and there has been no declaration of a new caliph by now, there is not likely to be in the next 3 weeks. If he's alive, he would have to be killed and replaced officially in three weeks. Unlikely.

So-called ISIS (and other terrorist groups) have a track record of obfuscating details of the deaths of their leaders to ensure that their organizations appear unaffected by actions against them. Local sources in Syria, indicate he was killed by Russian action in early July, so it appears likely they will be able to keep the truth hidden until Oct 1.
Middle bucket down 10% for passage of time. Perhaps I was wrong and he is more useful alive rather than dead.

Recent events in Mosul and Raqqa suggest that ISIS's current pillar of power is collapsing. Reports of Baghdadi's death have already surfaced and ISIS's influence continues to recede. Most ISIS related attacks are lone wolfs whose main motivation is the propaganda released by ISIS. If Baghdadi is really dead, an internal power struggle will most likely occur which could split the faction producing an entirely new organization altogether.
Maintaining forecast:

This question is somewhat undefined. I am interpreting this to be proclaimed by ISIS as a group. In order for that to occur, ISIS would have to have consensus on who the caliph is. More importantly however, the Caliphate only makes sense with a state to attach it to and it seems unlikely another one would be proclaimed as ISIS is losing control of territory and on the verge of ceasing to be a state.

Three questions: is Baghdadi dead? Will they name a new caliph (one person) to replace him? Will they do so by 1 October? 50 percent chance he is dead. If he is dead, 90 percent chance they decide on one person to replace him (rather than rule by committee), 70 percent chance they decide on his replacement by 1 October

Given IS's talent for PR I think it is unwise to completely reject the notion of a potential successor not embracing the title of Caliph, regardless of their theological training. To reject it would be to deny the existence of the state and hence admit to the ground they have lost. Alternatively, the title is in essence figurative in any case and without physical title, so why not pass it on?

Expanding slightly on what @Wildwood2000 said: From a New York Times op-Ed article: “the Islamic State’s real power resided not in religious extremists like Mr. Baghdadi but in a corps of former Saddam Hussein loyalists. These ex-Baathists, with a talent for eye-catching violence and unsurpassed knowledge of the inner workings of Iraqi society, kept the Islamic State alive through lean years before leading it to sweeping victories following the American departure from Iraq.” “Almost all of the ex-Baathist leaders are dead, as are most of their immediate lieutenants. This represents a key difference between IS today and Al-Qaeda in 2011. When Osama Bin Laden died, many of his deputies were around to keep the organization running” “The Islamic State’s most obvious successors might seem to be it’s network of affiliates. The biggest of which is based in eastern Libya” (https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/20/opinion/isis-abu-bakr-al-baghdadi.html?_r=0)

Clearly he knew that the Raqqa offensive was about to begin so it would be strange for him to remain in the area and not head to a “safe place.” Secondly, meeting in a big group (which Russia claimed happened) would attract a lot of attention. However, I could be proven completely wrong.

Or if there are other ways people are classifying the potential outcomes (airstrike success rate in killing specific leaders across all countries, perhaps?) I'd love to hear it!

[...] In the end, he will either be killed or captured, he will not be able to remain underground forever," said Lahur Talabany, the head of counter-terrorism at the Kurdistan Regional Government, the Kurdish autonomous region in northern Iraq. Lowering slightly probability of another caliph being declared after Baghdadi’s death.

Assuming he is not captured or killed in a special raid (highly unlikely), I believe that in the event of his death, ISIS will be slow to announce his death and proclaim a new leader. This could be for a variety of reasons including infighting and different factions supporting other candidates.

“Iranian-backed Shi’ite paramilitary forces are fighting IS along the Syrain border where Baghdadi is believed to be hiding, according to US and Iraqi officials” (http://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-iraq-mosul-idUSKBN18M2E5?il=0). This supports the coalitions assertion that they are “hunting” Baghdadi.

Based on reports of his potential capture back in April, it seems likely that IF caught, he would be executed and a new caliph would be chosen. Whether that proclamation would come before or after his death is hard to say. If those reports are false, as the case may be, it is unlikely that anyone else would become caliph.

Increasing the probability that Baghdadi is targeted after terrorist attack in Manchester. I believe tech companies will be more forthcoming, interrogation rules eased, and money and resources made available to accelerate locating Baghdadi. https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/lone-attacker-detonated-device-at-manchester-concert-killing-22-including-children/2017/05/23/027d414c-3f57-11e7-b29f-f40ffced2ddb_story.html?utm_term=.00a46ee8fcf5

ERBIL, Kurdistan Region — Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi abandoning his soldiers who are continuing to die for him in "territory that he has escaped from himself" is "a fool’s errand," the international coalition to defeat ISIS has told Rudaw, given the $25 million reward for information that leads to the self-proclaimed caliph of the Islamic State. “A large number of ISIS militants have surrendered to the security forces and it is ongoing,” said Najim al-Jabouri, the Iraqi commander of the Nineveh Operations Command in early April. “Upon the request of the surrendering militants, the general commander of the armed forces has guaranteed the militants that they will be tried just and their lives will be protected until the court has issued their verdicts per their crimes.” __________________________ COMMENTS: ISIS militants may have very little appetite for a new leader after these brutal battles, especially if the incumbent abandoned them.

Maintaining current forecast: According to a report: Baghdadi urged his fellow jihadists “to head towards Raqqa to repel the attack of atheist Kurds, the Crusader Coalition, and agents of the Cross on it.” The message was delivered in a so-called “Khutbah”, a sermon that preaches Islamic tradition and was meant to “motivate muslims and incite them to fight”, according to the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights. He's shown himself to be unwilling to be surrounded and die, as seen in his escape from Mosul. Therefore, he won't die until the entirety of Isis territory is captures, and/or the US gets a big intelligence break, which doesn't seem likely at this moment. Moreover, our drone campaign against Isis senior leadership means that he has fewer potential challengers for the title.
Baghdadi is a person like cats with seven lives I do not think to reach him before the battle of al rkka captial of khlafa and even then he can stay until he is betrayed and ashamed
It all comes down to the fate of Mosul and how Daesh handles the loss of the site where they declared their caliphate.
Progress made against ISIS recently makes his death much more likely than at the beginning of the year. It seems unlikely that the movement will die with its titular head.
Slightly lowering the probability of another caliph being declared while Baghdadi is alive:

Given the command structure of ISIS and the "cult like" communication structure is is not feasible or logical to forecast that such a proclamation would be announced with him alive. The high level of certainty is a reflection of the relatively slow pace of 'destruction" facing ISIS in the region where he is presumed to still be.

Two US soldiers died in a raid in Afghanistan on April 26th. “Captain Davis said the target of Wednesdays raid was Abdul Hasib, whom Defense Department officials called the emir of ISIS in Afghanistan. Pentagon officials could not confirm that he was killed in the operation” (https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/28/world/middleeast/american-soldiers-afghanistan.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Fus&action=click&contentCollection=us&region=stream&module=stream_unit&version=latest&contentPlacement=20&pgtype=sectionfront) Another example of the US using special ops raids to kill IS leadership.

Increasing slightly the probability of another caliph being declared before 1 October after Baghdadi’s death. According to a report on iraqinews.com, a Syrian activist said “dozens of IS members were either killed or wounded in the Syrian province of Deir ez-Zour by airstrikes conducted by the international coalition, which are believed to be carried out to target the groups supreme leader Baghdadi. The international coalition intensified air strikes on Deir ez-Zour on the background of the news that talked about the escape of the leader of IS, from Iraq to Syria” (http://www.iraqinews.com/arab-world-news/us-led-coalition-conducts-15-airstrikes-deir-ez-zour-targets-al-baghdadi/). I’m not sure on the credibility of this information, however one would expect the coalition to intensify airstrikes in an area where Baghdadi is rumoured/known to be.

It's highly unlikely that another caliph can arise while al-Baghdadi is alive, as any perceived threat to his own caliphate would be eliminated. If al-Baghdadi is killed by the coalition, it will signal a turning point with ISIS, potentially an OPSEC problem, and make it unlikely for any other candidate to willingly step up and risk being eliminated the same way. Informal local leaders would likely replace the centralized caliph.

Hey, if Erdogan proclaims himself caliph, will that count? That's how al-Baghdadi got the gig. Passive-voice verbs are so unhelpful.

I'm looking to South East Asia for the emergence of a challenger to Bagdadi. I'm looking for a convocation or Islamic scholars to issue forth a Fatah either setting out a course to ascend or declAring him apostate. Lacking those the Caliph may simply rot away.

al-Baghdadi will have to be dead for a new caliph. He will not hand over power peacefully. There is currently no one individual who is as charismatic as al-Baghdadi and will be able to overthrow him from power. He is also a member of the Quraysh tribe, who are the traditional descendants of Muhammed. They would need to find an individual from this tribe with his charisma to replace him.
The situation in Syria got even more chaotic in the last weeks. This can only favor Islamic State and thus decrease the chance of its leader being replaced or assassinated.
Bagdadhi may be able to hang-out somewhere and not die. Who knows?

If seriously, injured, his replacement might be named. Given the fact, he is a hunted man, and the engagement rules seemed to have been loosened (accepting higher civilian deaths for high value targets), he may meet his maker sooner than later. So, this could lead to a replacement. he may have already named a successor.

As Secretary Tillerson recently said at the Ministerial plenary for the Global Coalition Working to Defeat ISIS, “Nearly all of Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi’s deputies are now dead…it is only a matter of time before Baghdadi himself meets the same fate” (https://www.state.gov/secretary/remarks/2017/03/269039.htm). It is clear that Trumps administration is stepping up the fight against IS. “An unspecified number of combat soldiers from the US Army’s 82nd Airborne division have been ordered to northern Iraq” (http://www.militarytimes.com/articles/82nd-airborne-mosul-iraq-islamic-state) - some media outlets are saying 200 but not citing specific sources. In addition to Syria: “The US is sending an additional 400 troops to Syria…represents a near-doubling of the number of American troops there.” (https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/09/world/middleeast/us-troops-syria.html).
